des. The series was created and executive produced by [[Josh Pate]], [[Jonas Pate]], and [[Shannon Burke (writer)|Shannon Burke]].<ref name=\"SeriesOrder\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/05/outer-banks-charles-esten-chase-stokes-madelyn-cline-cast-netflix-ya-drama-series-1202606614/|title='Outer Banks': Charles Esten, Chase Stokes, Madelyn Cline Among 8 Cast In Netflix YA Drama Series|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|first=Denise|last=Petski|date=May 3, 2019|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref> The series was released on April 15, 2020.<ref name=\"ReleaseDate\">{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/entertainment/tv/2020/03/19/netflix-april-2020-new-and-departing-shows-and-movies/2873812001/|title=Netflix: Everything coming (and disappearing) in April 2020 (including 'Matrix,' 'BlackAF')|work=[[USA Today]]|first=Kelly|last=Lawler|date=March 19, 2020|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Casting===\nAlongside the initial series announcement, it was reported that Chase Stokes, Madelyn Cline, Madison Bailey, Jonathan Daviss, Rudy Pankow, [[Charles Esten]], [[Austin North]], and Drew Starkey were cast in starring roles.<ref name=\"SeriesOrder\"/> On July 2, 2019, Caroline Arapoglou joined the cast in a recurring role.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/07/outer-banks-caroline-arapoglou-recur-netflix-ya-drama-series-1202641411/|title='Outer Banks': Caroline Arapoglou To Recur In Netflix YA Drama Series|work=Deadline Hollywood|first=Denise|last=Petski|date=July 2, 2019|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\n[[Principal photography]] for the series began on May 1, 2019 in [[Charleston, South Carolina]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestate.com/entertainment/tv/article229605989.html|title=Why new Netflix show about the Outer Banks is filming in SC, and how you can be in it|work=[[The State (newspaper)|The State]]|first=Noah|last=Feit|date=April 23, 2019|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nOn Rotten Tomatoes, the series holds an approval rating of 69% based on 13 reviews, with an average rating of 6.8/10. The website's critical consensus reads, \"''Outer Banks''{{'}} over-the-top melodrama is balanced out by a strong sense of adventure that's bound to hook those looking to capture that summer feeling.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/outer_banks/s01|title=Outer Banks: Season 1 (2020)|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=April 18, 2020}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], it has a weighted average score of 63 out of 100 based on 7 reviews, indicating \"generally favorable reviews\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/outer-banks/season-1|title=Outer Banks: Season 1|work=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=April 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Netflix title|80236318}}\n* {{IMDb title|10293938}}\n\n{{Netflix original current series}}\n\n[[Category:2020 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2020s American teen drama television series]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Media portrayals of the upper class]]\n[[Category:Media portrayals of the working class]]\n[[Category:Netflix original programming]]\n[[Category:Television shows filmed in South Carolina]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Working-class culture in the United States]]\n{{US-tv-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Marcoasxd", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Outer_Banks_(TV_series)"}
{"title_page": "Magnesium chloride", "text_new": "{{chembox\n| Watchedfields = changed\n| verifiedrevid = 459589655\n| ImageFile1 = Magnesium chloride.jpg\n| ImageFile2 = Cadmium-chloride-3D-balls.png\n| OtherNames = Magnesium dichloride\n|Section1={{Chembox Identifiers\n| Abbreviations = \n| CASNo = 7786-30-3\n| CASNo_Ref = {{cascite|correct|CAS}}\n| CASNo2_Ref = {{cascite|changed|??}}\n| CASNo2 = 7791-18-6\n| CASNo2_Comment = (hexahydrate) <!--also verified against the Chemical Abstracts Service list -->\n| EINECS = \n| PubChem = 24584\n| ChEMBL_Ref = {{ebicite|changed|EBI}}\n| ChEMBL = 1200547\n| ChemSpiderID_Ref = {{chemspidercite|correct|chemspider}}\n| ChemSpiderID = 22987\n| ChEBI_Ref = {{ebicite|correct|EBI}}\n| ChEBI = 6636\n| SMILES = [Mg+2].[Cl-].[Cl-]\n| InChI = InChI=1S/2ClH.Mg/h2*1H;/q;;+2/p-2\n| StdInChI_Ref = {{stdinchicite|correct|chemspider}}\n| StdInChI = 1S/2ClH.Mg/h2*1H;/q;;+2/p-2\n| StdInChIKey_Ref = {{stdinchicite|correct|chemspider}}\n| StdInChIKey = TWRXJAOTZQYOKJ-UHFFFAOYSA-L \n| RTECS = OM2975000\n| Gmelin = 9305\n  }}\n|Section2={{Chembox Properties\n| Formula = MgCl<sub>2</sub>\n| MolarMass = 95.211 g/mol (anhydrous)<br/>203.31 g/mol (hexahydrate)\n| Appearance = white or colourless crystalline solid\n| Density = 2.32 g/cm<sup>3</sup> (anhydrous) <br> 1.569 g/cm<sup>3</sup> (hexahydrate)\n| MeltingPtC = 714\n| MeltingPt_notes = {{convert|117|C|F K}} (hexahydrate) <br> on rapid heating: slow heating leads to decomposition from {{convert|300|C|F K}}\n| BoilingPtC = 1412\n| BoilingPt_notes = \n| Solubility = ''anhydrous'' <br>52.9 g/100 mL (0 \u00b0C) <br> 54.3 g/100 mL (20&nbsp;\u00b0C) <br> 72.6 g/100 mL (100&nbsp;\u00b0C) <hr> ''hexahydrate'' <br> 235 g/100 mL (20&nbsp;\u00b0C)\n| Solubility1 = 7.4 g/100 mL (30&nbsp;\u00b0C)\n| Solvent1 = ethanol\n| SolubleOther = slightly soluble in [[acetone]], [[pyridine]]\n| LogP = \n| HenryConstant = \n| RefractIndex = 1.675 (anhydrous) <br> 1.569 (hexahydrate)\n| MagSus = \u221247.4\u00b710<sup>\u22126</sup> cm<sup>3</sup>/mol\n  }}\n|Section3={{Chembox Structure\n| CrystalStruct = [[Cadmium chloride#Crystal structure|CdCl<sub>2</sub>]]\n| Coordination = (octahedral, 6-coordinate)\n| MolShape = \n  }}\n|Section5={{Chembox Thermochemistry\n| DeltaHf = \u2212641.1 kJ/mol\n| DeltaGf = \u2212591.6 kJ/mol\n| Entropy = 89.88 J/(mol K)\n| HeatCapacity = 71.09 J/(mol K)\n  }}\n|Section6={{Chembox Pharmacology\n| ATCCode_prefix = A12\n| ATCCode_suffix = CC01\n| ATC_Supplemental = {{ATC|B05|XA11}}\n}}\n|Section7={{Chembox Hazards\n| ExternalSDS = [http://www.inchem.org/documents/icsc/icsc/eics0764.htm ICSC 0764]\n| EUClass = \n| MainHazards = Irritant\n| NFPA-H = 1\n| NFPA-F = 0\n| NFPA-R = 0\n| NFPA-S = \n| RPhrases = {{R36}}, {{R37}}, {{R38}}\n| SPhrases = {{S26}}, {{S37}}, {{S39}}\n| FlashPt = Non-flammable\n| LD50 = 2800 mg/kg (oral, rat)\n| PEL = \n  }}\n|Section8={{Chembox Related\n| OtherAnions = [[Magnesium fluoride]]<br/>[[Magnesium bromide]]<br/>[[Magnesium iodide]]\n| OtherCations = [[Beryllium chloride]]<br/>[[Calcium chloride]]<br/>[[Strontium chloride]]<br/>[[Barium chloride]]<br/>[[Radium chloride]]\n| OtherFunction = \n| OtherFunction_label = \n| OtherCompounds = \n  }}\n}}\n'''Magnesium chloride''' is the name for the [[chemical compound]] with the [[chemical formula|formula]] MgCl<sub>2</sub> and its various [[water of hydration|hydrate]]s MgCl<sub>2</sub>(H<sub>2</sub>O)<sub>''x''</sub>. These salts are typical ionic [[halide]]s, being highly soluble in water. The hydrated magnesium chloride can be extracted from [[brine]] or [[sea water]]. In North America, magnesium chloride is produced primarily from [[Great Salt Lake]] brine. It is extracted in a similar process from the [[Dead Sea]] in the [[Jordan Valley (Middle East)|Jordan Valley]]. Magnesium chloride, as the natural mineral [[bischofite]], is also extracted (by solution mining) out of ancient seabeds, for example, the [[Zechstein]] seabed in northwest Europe. Some magnesium chloride is made from solar evaporation of seawater. [[Anhydrous]] magnesium chloride is the principal precursor to magnesium metal, which is produced on a large scale. Hydrated magnesium chloride is the form most readily available.\n\n==Structure, preparation, and general properties==\nMgCl<sub>2</sub> crystallizes in the [[cadmium chloride]] motif, which features octahedral Mg centers. Several hydrates are known with the formula MgCl<sub>2</sub>(H<sub>2</sub>O)<sub>''x''</sub>, and each loses water at higher temperatures: ''x'' = 12 (\u221216.4&nbsp;\u00b0C), 8 (\u22123.4&nbsp;\u00b0C), 6 (116.7&nbsp;\u00b0C), 4 (181&nbsp;\u00b0C), 2 (about 300&nbsp;\u00b0C).<ref>Holleman, A. F.; Wiberg, E. ''Inorganic Chemistry'' Academic Press: San Diego, 2001. {{ISBN|0-12-352651-5}}.</ref> In the hexahydrate, the Mg<sup>2+</sup> is also [[Octahedral molecular geometry|octahedral]], but is coordinated to six water [[ligand]]s.<ref>Wells, A. F. (1984) ''Structural Inorganic Chemistry'', Oxford: Clarendon Press. {{ISBN|0-19-855370-6}}.</ref> The thermal dehydration of the hydrates MgCl<sub>2</sub>(H<sub>2</sub>O)<sub>x</sub> (''x'' = 6, 12) does not occur straightforwardly.<ref>See notes in Rieke, R. D.; Bales, S. E.; Hudnall, P. M.; Burns, T. P.; Poindexter, G. S. \"Highly Reactive Magnesium for the Preparation of Grignard Reagents: 1-Norbornane Acid\", ''Organic Syntheses'', Collected Volume 6, p. 845 (1988). {{cite web |url=http://www.orgsyn.org/orgsyn/pdfs/CV6P0845.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2007-05-10 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930212159/http://www.orgsyn.org/orgsyn/pdfs/CV6P0845.pdf |archivedate=2007-09-30 }}</ref>  Anhydrous MgCl<sub>2</sub> is produced industrially by heating the chloride salt of hexammine complex [Mg(NH<sub>3</sub>)<sub>6</sub>]<sup>2+</sup>.<ref name = ullmann/>\n\nAs suggested by the existence of some hydrates, anhydrous MgCl<sub>2</sub> is a [[Lewis acid]], although a weak one.\n\nIn the [[Dow process]], magnesium chloride is regenerated from magnesium hydroxide using [[hydrochloric acid]]:\n: [[Magnesium hydroxide|Mg(OH)<sub>2</sub>]]<sub>([[solid|s]])</sub> + 2 HCl \u2192 MgCl<sub>2([[aqueous|aq]])</sub> + 2 [[water|H<sub>2</sub>O]]<sub>([[liquid|l]])</sub>\nIt can also be prepared from [[magnesium carbonate]] by a similar reaction.\n\nDerivatives with tetrahedral Mg<sup>2+</sup> are less common. Examples include salts of ([[tetraethylammonium]])<sub>2</sub>MgCl<sub>4</sub> and [[adduct]]s such as MgCl<sub>2</sub>([[TMEDA]]).<ref>N. N. Greenwood, A. Earnshaw, ''Chemistry of the Elements'', Pergamon Press, 1984.</ref>\n\n==Applications==\n===Precursor to Mg metal===\nMgCl<sub>2</sub> is the main precursor to metallic magnesium.  The conversion is effected by [[electrolysis]]:<ref name = ullmann>{{Ullmann | title = Magnesium Compounds | author1 = Margarete Seeger | author2 = Walter Otto | author3 = Wilhelm Flick | author4 = Friedrich Bickelhaupt | author5 = Otto S. Akkerman | doi = 10.1002/14356007.a15_595.pub2}}</ref><ref name=\"Hill\">Hill, Petrucci, McCreary, Perry, ''General Chemistry'', 4th ed., Pearson/Prentice Hall, Upper Saddle River, New Jersey, USA.</ref>\n: MgCl<sub>2</sub> \u2192 Mg + Cl<sub>2</sub>\nThis process is practiced on a substantial scale.\n\n=== {{anchor|Use in dust and erosion control}} Dust and erosion control ===\nMagnesium chloride is one of many substances used for dust control, [[soil stabilization]], and [[Aeolian processes|wind erosion]] mitigation.<ref name=\"fs.fed.us\">{{cite web |url=http://www.fs.fed.us/eng/pubs/html/99771207/99771207.html#EI |title=Dust Palliative Selection and Application Guide |publisher=Fs.fed.us |date= |accessdate=2017-10-18}}</ref> When magnesium chloride is applied to roads and bare soil areas, both positive and negative performance issues occur which are related to many application factors.<ref name=\"nrcs.usda.gov\">https://www.nrcs.usda.gov/Internet/FSE_DOCUMENTS/stelprdb1043546.pdf</ref>\n\n===Catalyst support===\n[[Ziegler-Natta catalysts]], used commercially to produce [[polyolefin]]s, contain MgCl<sub>2</sub> as a [[catalyst support]].<ref>{{cite book\n|chapter=Commercially Available Metal Alkyls and Their Use in Polyolefin Catalysts\n|editors=Ray Hoff, Robert T. Mathers\n|author=Dennis B. Malpass\n|doi=10.1002/9780470504437.ch1\n|year=2010\n|publisher= John Wiley & Sons, Inc.\n|title= Handbook of Transition Metal Polymerization Catalysts|pages=1\u201328\n|isbn=9780470504437\n}}</ref>  The introduction of MgCl<sub>2</sub> supports increases the activity of traditional catalysts and allowed the development of highly stereospecific catalysts for the production of [[polypropylene]].<ref>{{cite journal |title=The Discovery and Progress of MgCl<sub>2</sub>-Supported TiCl<sub>4</sub> Catalysts |author=Norio Kashiwa |doi=10.1002/pola.10962 |journal=Journal of Polymer Science A |volume=42 |issue=1 |year=2004 |pages=1\u20138|bibcode=2004JPoSA..42....1K }}</ref>\n\n=== {{anchor|Use in ice control}} Ice control ===\n[[File:Snow-removal-cleveland-1.jpg|thumb|left|Picture of truck applying liquid de-icer (magnesium chloride) to city streets]][[File:Cleveland-snow-removal-1.jpg|thumb|left|Picture of solid form of rock salt used for ice removal on streets]]\n\nMagnesium chloride is used for low-temperature de-icing of [[highway]]s, [[sidewalk]]s, and [[parking lot]]s. When highways are treacherous due to icy conditions, magnesium chloride helps to prevent the ice bond, allowing [[snow]] plows to clear the roads more efficiently.\n\nMagnesium chloride is used in three ways for pavement ice control: Anti-icing, when maintenance professionals spread it onto roads before a snow storm to prevent snow from sticking and ice from forming; prewetting, which means a liquid formulation of magnesium chloride is sprayed directly onto salt as it is being spread onto roadway pavement, wetting the salt so that it sticks to the road; and pretreating, when magnesium chloride and salt are mixed together before they are loaded onto trucks and spread onto paved roads. Calcium chloride damages concrete twice as fast as magnesium chloride.<ref>Jain, J., Olek, J., Janusz, A., and Jozwiak-Niedzwiedzka, D., \"Effects of Deicing Salt Solutions on Physical Properties of Pavement Concretes\", Transportation Research Record: Journal of the Transportation Research Board, No. 2290, Transportation Research Board of the National Academies, Washington, D.C., 2012, pp. 69-75. {{doi|10.3141/2290-09}}.</ref>\n\n=== {{anchor|Nutritional supplement}} Nutrition and medicine ===\nMagnesium chloride is used in [[nutraceutical]] and [[Magnesium (pharmaceutical preparation)|pharmaceutical preparations]].\n\n=== {{anchor|Culinary use}} Cuisine ===\nMagnesium chloride ([[E number|E511]]<ref name=ceua>{{cite web\n| last = [[Food Standard Agency]]\n| authorlink = \n| title = Current EU approved additives and their E Numbers\n| publisher = \n| date = \n| url = http://www.food.gov.uk/safereating/chemsafe/additivesbranch/enumberlist\n| doi =\n| accessdate = 22 March 2010\n}}</ref>) is an important [[Coagulation|coagulant]] used in the preparation of [[tofu]] from [[soy milk]]. In Japan it is sold as ''[[nigari]]'' ([[:ja:\u306b\u304c\u308a|\u306b\u304c\u308a]], derived from the Japanese word for \"bitter\"), a white powder produced from seawater after the [[sodium chloride]] has been removed, and the water evaporated. In China, it is called ''lushui'' ([[wikt:\u5364\u6c34|\u5364\u6c34]]). ''Nigari'' or ''lushui'' consists mostly of magnesium chloride, with some [[magnesium sulfate]] and other trace elements. It is also an ingredient in baby formula milk.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://abbottnutrition.com/brands/products/similac-expert-care-alimentum |title=Listed under ingredients for Similac Hypoallergenic Infant Formula with Iron (Abbott Nutrition) |publisher=abbottnutrition.com |accessdate=2013-07-22}}</ref>\n\n=== Gardening and horticulture ===\nBecause magnesium is a mobile nutrient, magnesium chloride can be effectively used as a substitute for [[magnesium sulfate]] (Epsom salt) to help correct magnesium deficiency in plants via [[foliar feeding]]. The recommended dose of magnesium chloride is smaller than the recommended dose of magnesium sulfate (20 g/l).<ref>{{cite journal |title=Comparison of Magnesium Sulfate and THIS Mg Chelate Foliar Sprays |publisher=Pubs.aic.ca |date=1970-01-01 |doi=10.4141/cjps85-018 }}</ref> This is due primarily to the chlorine present in magnesium chloride, which can easily reach toxic levels if over-applied or applied too often.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ext.colostate.edu/pubs/garden/07425.html |title=Magnesium Chloride Toxicity in Trees |publisher=Ext.colostate.edu |date= |accessdate=2017-10-18}}</ref>\n\nIt has been found that higher concentrations of magnesium in [[tomato]] and some [[Black pepper|pepper]] plants can make them more susceptible to disease caused by infection of the bacterium ''[[Xanthomonas campestris]]'', since magnesium is essential for bacterial growth.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.apsnet.org/publications/plantdisease/backissues/Documents/1983Articles/PlantDisease67n06_623.pdf |title=Effect of Foliar and Soil Magnesium Application on Bacterial Leaf Spot of Peppers |date= |accessdate=2017-10-18}}</ref>\n\n==Occurrence==\n[[File:Sea salt-e-dp hg.svg|thumb|right|Chemical composition of sea salt|alt=Mass fractions of various salt ions in seawater]]\nMagnesium values in natural [[seawater]] are between 1250 and 1350&nbsp;mg/l, around 3.7% of the total seawater mineral content. [[Dead Sea]] minerals contain a significantly higher magnesium chloride ratio, 50.8%. Carbonates and calcium are essential for all growth of [[coral]]s, [[coralline algae]], [[clam]]s, and [[invertebrate]]s. Magnesium can be depleted by [[mangrove]] plants and the use of excessive [[limewater]] or by going beyond natural calcium, [[alkalinity]], and [[pH]] values.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.advancedaquarist.com/issues/oct2003/chem.htm |title=Aquarium Chemistry: Magnesium In Reef Aquaria \u2014 Advanced Aquarist &#124; Aquarist Magazine and Blog |publisher=Advancedaquarist.com |date=2003-10-15 |accessdate=2013-01-17}}</ref>\n\n== Toxicology ==\nMagnesium ions are bitter-tasting, and magnesium chloride solutions are bitter in varying degrees, depending on the concentration of magnesium.\n\nMagnesium toxicity from magnesium salts is rare in healthy individuals with a normal diet, because excess magnesium is readily excreted in [[urine]] by the [[kidneys]]. A few cases of [[oral administration|oral]] magnesium toxicity have been described in persons with normal renal function ingesting large amounts of magnesium salts, but it is rare. If a large amount of magnesium chloride is eaten, it will have effects similar to [[magnesium sulfate]], causing diarrhea, although the sulfate also contributes to the laxative effect in magnesium sulfate, so the effect from the chloride is not as severe.\n\n=== Plant toxicity ===\n\nChloride (Cl<sup>\u2212</sup>) and magnesium (Mg<sup>2+</sup>) are both essential nutrients important for normal plant growth. Too much of either nutrient may harm a plant, although foliar chloride concentrations are more strongly related with foliar damage than magnesium. High concentrations of MgCl<sub>2</sub> ions in the soil may be toxic or change water relationships such that the plant cannot easily accumulate water and nutrients. Once inside the plant, chloride moves through the water-conducting system and accumulates at the margins of leaves or needles, where dieback occurs first. Leaves are weakened or killed, which can lead to the death of the tree.<ref name=\"colostate1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ext.colostate.edu/pubs/garden/07425.html |title=Publications \u2013 ExtensionExtension |publisher=Ext.colostate.edu |accessdate=2017-10-18 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924005210/http://www.ext.colostate.edu/pubs/garden/07425.html |archive-date=2015-09-24 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Locomotive boiler problem==\nThe presence of dissolved magnesium chloride in the well water ([[Water well#Drilled wells|bore water]]) used in locomotive boilers on the [[Trans-Australian Railway]] caused serious and expensive maintenance problems during the steam era. At no point along its route does the line cross a permanent freshwater watercourse, so bore water had to be relied on. No inexpensive treatment for the highly mineralised water was available, and locomotive boilers were lasting less than a quarter of the time normally expected.<ref>{{cite news |title=Overland Locomotive:Feed Water Problems |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article3880541 |accessdate=2014-03-11 |newspaper=The Argus |date=1927-03-21}}</ref> In the days of steam locomotion, about half the total train load was water for the engine. The line's operator, [[Commonwealth Railways]], was an early adopter of the [[Diesel locomotive#Diesel-electric|diesel-electric locomotive]].\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Acceptable daily intake]]\n* [[Magnesium oil]]\n\n== Notes and references ==\n;Notes\n{{reflist|30em}}\n;References\n* ''Handbook of Chemistry and Physics'', 71st edition, CRC Press, Ann Arbor, Michigan, 1990.\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20040314010235/http://www.usda.gov/rus/electric/engineering/2001/magnesium_chloride.htm Magnesium Chloride as a De-Icing Agent]\n* [http://www.mistralni.co.uk/msds/mmgc200.gdsbusapb.pdf MSDS file for Magnesium Chloride Hexahydrate]\n\n{{Magnesium compounds}}\n{{Chlorides}}\n{{Mineral supplements}}\n\n[[Category:Chlorides]]\n[[Category:Magnesium compounds]]\n[[Category:Metal halides]]\n[[Category:Deliquescent substances]]\n[[Category:Food additives]]\n[[Category:E-number additives]]\n", "text_old": "{{chembox\n| Watchedfields = changed\n| verifiedrevid = 459589655\n| ImageFile1 = Magnesium chloride.jpg\n| ImageFile2 = Cadmium-chloride-3D-balls.png\n| OtherNames = Magnesium dichloride\n|Section1={{Chembox Identifiers\n| Abbreviations = \n| CASNo = 7786-30-3\n| CASNo_Ref = {{cascite|correct|CAS}}\n| CASNo2_Ref = {{cascite|changed|??}}\n| CASNo2 = 7791-18-6\n| CASNo2_Comment = (hexahydrate) <!--also verified against the Chemical Abstracts Service list -->\n| EINECS = \n| PubChem = 24584\n| ChEMBL_Ref = {{ebicite|changed|EBI}}\n| ChEMBL = 1200547\n| ChemSpiderID_Ref = {{chemspidercite|correct|chemspider}}\n| ChemSpiderID = 22987\n| ChEBI_Ref = {{ebicite|correct|EBI}}\n| ChEBI = 6636\n| SMILES = [Mg+2].[Cl-].[Cl-]\n| InChI = InChI=1S/2ClH.Mg/h2*1H;/q;;+2/p-2\n| StdInChI_Ref = {{stdinchicite|correct|chemspider}}\n| StdInChI = 1S/2ClH.Mg/h2*1H;/q;;+2/p-2\n| StdInChIKey_Ref = {{stdinchicite|correct|chemspider}}\n| StdInChIKey = TWRXJAOTZQYOKJ-UHFFFAOYSA-L \n| RTECS = OM2975000\n| Gmelin = 9305\n  }}\n|Section2={{Chembox Properties\n| Formula = MgCl<sub>2</sub>\n| MolarMass = 95.211 g/mol (anhydrous)<br/>203.31 g/mol (hexahydrate)\n| Appearance = white or colourless crystalline solid\n| Density = 2.32 g/cm<sup>3</sup> (anhydrous) <br> 1.569 g/cm<sup>3</sup> (hexahydrate)\n| MeltingPtC = 714\n| MeltingPt_notes = {{convert|117|C|F K}} (hexahydrate) <br> on rapid heating: slow heating leads to decomposition from {{convert|300|C|F K}}\n| BoilingPtC = 1412\n| BoilingPt_notes = \n| Solubility = ''anhydrous'' 52.9 g/100 mL (0 \u00b0C) <br> <br> 54.3 g/100 mL (20&nbsp;\u00b0C) <br> 72.6 g/100 mL (100&nbsp;\u00b0C) <hr> ''hexahydrate'' <br> 235 g/100 mL (20&nbsp;\u00b0C)\n| Solubility1 = 7.4 g/100 mL (30&nbsp;\u00b0C)\n| Solvent1 = ethanol\n| SolubleOther = slightly soluble in [[acetone]], [[pyridine]]\n| LogP = \n| HenryConstant = \n| RefractIndex = 1.675 (anhydrous) <br> 1.569 (hexahydrate)\n| MagSus = \u221247.4\u00b710<sup>\u22126</sup> cm<sup>3</sup>/mol\n  }}\n|Section3={{Chembox Structure\n| CrystalStruct = [[Cadmium chloride#Crystal structure|CdCl<sub>2</sub>]]\n| Coordination = (octahedral, 6-coordinate)\n| MolShape = \n  }}\n|Section5={{Chembox Thermochemistry\n| DeltaHf = \u2212641.1 kJ/mol\n| DeltaGf = \u2212591.6 kJ/mol\n| Entropy = 89.88 J/(mol K)\n| HeatCapacity = 71.09 J/(mol K)\n  }}\n|Section6={{Chembox Pharmacology\n| ATCCode_prefix = A12\n| ATCCode_suffix = CC01\n| ATC_Supplemental = {{ATC|B05|XA11}}\n}}\n|Section7={{Chembox Hazards\n| ExternalSDS = [http://www.inchem.org/documents/icsc/icsc/eics0764.htm ICSC 0764]\n| EUClass = \n| MainHazards = Irritant\n| NFPA-H = 1\n| NFPA-F = 0\n| NFPA-R = 0\n| NFPA-S = \n| RPhrases = {{R36}}, {{R37}}, {{R38}}\n| SPhrases = {{S26}}, {{S37}}, {{S39}}\n| FlashPt = Non-flammable\n| LD50 = 2800 mg/kg (oral, rat)\n| PEL = \n  }}\n|Section8={{Chembox Related\n| OtherAnions = [[Magnesium fluoride]]<br/>[[Magnesium bromide]]<br/>[[Magnesium iodide]]\n| OtherCations = [[Beryllium chloride]]<br/>[[Calcium chloride]]<br/>[[Strontium chloride]]<br/>[[Barium chloride]]<br/>[[Radium chloride]]\n| OtherFunction = \n| OtherFunction_label = \n| OtherCompounds = \n  }}\n}}\n'''Magnesium chloride''' is the name for the [[chemical compound]] with the [[chemical formula|formula]] MgCl<sub>2</sub> and its various [[water of hydration|hydrate]]s MgCl<sub>2</sub>(H<sub>2</sub>O)<sub>''x''</sub>. These salts are typical ionic [[halide]]s, being highly soluble in water. The hydrated magnesium chloride can be extracted from [[brine]] or [[sea water]]. In North America, magnesium chloride is produced primarily from [[Great Salt Lake]] brine. It is extracted in a similar process from the [[Dead Sea]] in the [[Jordan Valley (Middle East)|Jordan Valley]]. Magnesium chloride, as the natural mineral [[bischofite]], is also extracted (by solution mining) out of ancient seabeds, for example, the [[Zechstein]] seabed in northwest Europe. Some magnesium chloride is made from solar evaporation of seawater. [[Anhydrous]] magnesium chloride is the principal precursor to magnesium metal, which is produced on a large scale. Hydrated magnesium chloride is the form most readily available.\n\n==Structure, preparation, and general properties==\nMgCl<sub>2</sub> crystallizes in the [[cadmium chloride]] motif, which features octahedral Mg centers. Several hydrates are known with the formula MgCl<sub>2</sub>(H<sub>2</sub>O)<sub>''x''</sub>, and each loses water at higher temperatures: ''x'' = 12 (\u221216.4&nbsp;\u00b0C), 8 (\u22123.4&nbsp;\u00b0C), 6 (116.7&nbsp;\u00b0C), 4 (181&nbsp;\u00b0C), 2 (about 300&nbsp;\u00b0C).<ref>Holleman, A. F.; Wiberg, E. ''Inorganic Chemistry'' Academic Press: San Diego, 2001. {{ISBN|0-12-352651-5}}.</ref> In the hexahydrate, the Mg<sup>2+</sup> is also [[Octahedral molecular geometry|octahedral]], but is coordinated to six water [[ligand]]s.<ref>Wells, A. F. (1984) ''Structural Inorganic Chemistry'', Oxford: Clarendon Press. {{ISBN|0-19-855370-6}}.</ref> The thermal dehydration of the hydrates MgCl<sub>2</sub>(H<sub>2</sub>O)<sub>x</sub> (''x'' = 6, 12) does not occur straightforwardly.<ref>See notes in Rieke, R. D.; Bales, S. E.; Hudnall, P. M.; Burns, T. P.; Poindexter, G. S. \"Highly Reactive Magnesium for the Preparation of Grignard Reagents: 1-Norbornane Acid\", ''Organic Syntheses'', Collected Volume 6, p. 845 (1988). {{cite web |url=http://www.orgsyn.org/orgsyn/pdfs/CV6P0845.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2007-05-10 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930212159/http://www.orgsyn.org/orgsyn/pdfs/CV6P0845.pdf |archivedate=2007-09-30 }}</ref>  Anhydrous MgCl<sub>2</sub> is produced industrially by heating the chloride salt of hexammine complex [Mg(NH<sub>3</sub>)<sub>6</sub>]<sup>2+</sup>.<ref name = ullmann/>\n\nAs suggested by the existence of some hydrates, anhydrous MgCl<sub>2</sub> is a [[Lewis acid]], although a weak one.\n\nIn the [[Dow process]], magnesium chloride is regenerated from magnesium hydroxide using [[hydrochloric acid]]:\n: [[Magnesium hydroxide|Mg(OH)<sub>2</sub>]]<sub>([[solid|s]])</sub> + 2 HCl \u2192 MgCl<sub>2([[aqueous|aq]])</sub> + 2 [[water|H<sub>2</sub>O]]<sub>([[liquid|l]])</sub>\nIt can also be prepared from [[magnesium carbonate]] by a similar reaction.\n\nDerivatives with tetrahedral Mg<sup>2+</sup> are less common. Examples include salts of ([[tetraethylammonium]])<sub>2</sub>MgCl<sub>4</sub> and [[adduct]]s such as MgCl<sub>2</sub>([[TMEDA]]).<ref>N. N. Greenwood, A. Earnshaw, ''Chemistry of the Elements'', Pergamon Press, 1984.</ref>\n\n==Applications==\n===Precursor to Mg metal===\nMgCl<sub>2</sub> is the main precursor to metallic magnesium.  The conversion is effected by [[electrolysis]]:<ref name = ullmann>{{Ullmann | title = Magnesium Compounds | author1 = Margarete Seeger | author2 = Walter Otto | author3 = Wilhelm Flick | author4 = Friedrich Bickelhaupt | author5 = Otto S. Akkerman | doi = 10.1002/14356007.a15_595.pub2}}</ref><ref name=\"Hill\">Hill, Petrucci, McCreary, Perry, ''General Chemistry'', 4th ed., Pearson/Prentice Hall, Upper Saddle River, New Jersey, USA.</ref>\n: MgCl<sub>2</sub> \u2192 Mg + Cl<sub>2</sub>\nThis process is practiced on a substantial scale.\n\n=== {{anchor|Use in dust and erosion control}} Dust and erosion control ===\nMagnesium chloride is one of many substances used for dust control, [[soil stabilization]], and [[Aeolian processes|wind erosion]] mitigation.<ref name=\"fs.fed.us\">{{cite web |url=http://www.fs.fed.us/eng/pubs/html/99771207/99771207.html#EI |title=Dust Palliative Selection and Application Guide |publisher=Fs.fed.us |date= |accessdate=2017-10-18}}</ref> When magnesium chloride is applied to roads and bare soil areas, both positive and negative performance issues occur which are related to many application factors.<ref name=\"nrcs.usda.gov\">https://www.nrcs.usda.gov/Internet/FSE_DOCUMENTS/stelprdb1043546.pdf</ref>\n\n===Catalyst support===\n[[Ziegler-Natta catalysts]], used commercially to produce [[polyolefin]]s, contain MgCl<sub>2</sub> as a [[catalyst support]].<ref>{{cite book\n|chapter=Commercially Available Metal Alkyls and Their Use in Polyolefin Catalysts\n|editors=Ray Hoff, Robert T. Mathers\n|author=Dennis B. Malpass\n|doi=10.1002/9780470504437.ch1\n|year=2010\n|publisher= John Wiley & Sons, Inc.\n|title= Handbook of Transition Metal Polymerization Catalysts|pages=1\u201328\n|isbn=9780470504437\n}}</ref>  The introduction of MgCl<sub>2</sub> supports increases the activity of traditional catalysts and allowed the development of highly stereospecific catalysts for the production of [[polypropylene]].<ref>{{cite journal |title=The Discovery and Progress of MgCl<sub>2</sub>-Supported TiCl<sub>4</sub> Catalysts |author=Norio Kashiwa |doi=10.1002/pola.10962 |journal=Journal of Polymer Science A |volume=42 |issue=1 |year=2004 |pages=1\u20138|bibcode=2004JPoSA..42....1K }}</ref>\n\n=== {{anchor|Use in ice control}} Ice control ===\n[[File:Snow-removal-cleveland-1.jpg|thumb|left|Picture of truck applying liquid de-icer (magnesium chloride) to city streets]][[File:Cleveland-snow-removal-1.jpg|thumb|left|Picture of solid form of rock salt used for ice removal on streets]]\n\nMagnesium chloride is used for low-temperature de-icing of [[highway]]s, [[sidewalk]]s, and [[parking lot]]s. When highways are treacherous due to icy conditions, magnesium chloride helps to prevent the ice bond, allowing [[snow]] plows to clear the roads more efficiently.\n\nMagnesium chloride is used in three ways for pavement ice control: Anti-icing, when maintenance professionals spread it onto roads before a snow storm to prevent snow from sticking and ice from forming; prewetting, which means a liquid formulation of magnesium chloride is sprayed directly onto salt as it is being spread onto roadway pavement, wetting the salt so that it sticks to the road; and pretreating, when magnesium chloride and salt are mixed together before they are loaded onto trucks and spread onto paved roads. Calcium chloride damages concrete twice as fast as magnesium chloride.<ref>Jain, J., Olek, J., Janusz, A., and Jozwiak-Niedzwiedzka, D., \"Effects of Deicing Salt Solutions on Physical Properties of Pavement Concretes\", Transportation Research Record: Journal of the Transportation Research Board, No. 2290, Transportation Research Board of the National Academies, Washington, D.C., 2012, pp. 69-75. {{doi|10.3141/2290-09}}.</ref>\n\n=== {{anchor|Nutritional supplement}} Nutrition and medicine ===\nMagnesium chloride is used in [[nutraceutical]] and [[Magnesium (pharmaceutical preparation)|pharmaceutical preparations]].\n\n=== {{anchor|Culinary use}} Cuisine ===\nMagnesium chloride ([[E number|E511]]<ref name=ceua>{{cite web\n| last = [[Food Standard Agency]]\n| authorlink = \n| title = Current EU approved additives and their E Numbers\n| publisher = \n| date = \n| url = http://www.food.gov.uk/safereating/chemsafe/additivesbranch/enumberlist\n| doi =\n| accessdate = 22 March 2010\n}}</ref>) is an important [[Coagulation|coagulant]] used in the preparation of [[tofu]] from [[soy milk]]. In Japan it is sold as ''[[nigari]]'' ([[:ja:\u306b\u304c\u308a|\u306b\u304c\u308a]], derived from the Japanese word for \"bitter\"), a white powder produced from seawater after the [[sodium chloride]] has been removed, and the water evaporated. In China, it is called ''lushui'' ([[wikt:\u5364\u6c34|\u5364\u6c34]]). ''Nigari'' or ''lushui'' consists mostly of magnesium chloride, with some [[magnesium sulfate]] and other trace elements. It is also an ingredient in baby formula milk.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://abbottnutrition.com/brands/products/similac-expert-care-alimentum |title=Listed under ingredients for Similac Hypoallergenic Infant Formula with Iron (Abbott Nutrition) |publisher=abbottnutrition.com |accessdate=2013-07-22}}</ref>\n\n=== Gardening and horticulture ===\nBecause magnesium is a mobile nutrient, magnesium chloride can be effectively used as a substitute for [[magnesium sulfate]] (Epsom salt) to help correct magnesium deficiency in plants via [[foliar feeding]]. The recommended dose of magnesium chloride is smaller than the recommended dose of magnesium sulfate (20 g/l).<ref>{{cite journal |title=Comparison of Magnesium Sulfate and THIS Mg Chelate Foliar Sprays |publisher=Pubs.aic.ca |date=1970-01-01 |doi=10.4141/cjps85-018 }}</ref> This is due primarily to the chlorine present in magnesium chloride, which can easily reach toxic levels if over-applied or applied too often.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ext.colostate.edu/pubs/garden/07425.html |title=Magnesium Chloride Toxicity in Trees |publisher=Ext.colostate.edu |date= |accessdate=2017-10-18}}</ref>\n\nIt has been found that higher concentrations of magnesium in [[tomato]] and some [[Black pepper|pepper]] plants can make them more susceptible to disease caused by infection of the bacterium ''[[Xanthomonas campestris]]'', since magnesium is essential for bacterial growth.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.apsnet.org/publications/plantdisease/backissues/Documents/1983Articles/PlantDisease67n06_623.pdf |title=Effect of Foliar and Soil Magnesium Application on Bacterial Leaf Spot of Peppers |date= |accessdate=2017-10-18}}</ref>\n\n==Occurrence==\n[[File:Sea salt-e-dp hg.svg|thumb|right|Chemical composition of sea salt|alt=Mass fractions of various salt ions in seawater]]\nMagnesium values in natural [[seawater]] are between 1250 and 1350&nbsp;mg/l, around 3.7% of the total seawater mineral content. [[Dead Sea]] minerals contain a significantly higher magnesium chloride ratio, 50.8%. Carbonates and calcium are essential for all growth of [[coral]]s, [[coralline algae]], [[clam]]s, and [[invertebrate]]s. Magnesium can be depleted by [[mangrove]] plants and the use of excessive [[limewater]] or by going beyond natural calcium, [[alkalinity]], and [[pH]] values.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.advancedaquarist.com/issues/oct2003/chem.htm |title=Aquarium Chemistry: Magnesium In Reef Aquaria \u2014 Advanced Aquarist &#124; Aquarist Magazine and Blog |publisher=Advancedaquarist.com |date=2003-10-15 |accessdate=2013-01-17}}</ref>\n\n== Toxicology ==\nMagnesium ions are bitter-tasting, and magnesium chloride solutions are bitter in varying degrees, depending on the concentration of magnesium.\n\nMagnesium toxicity from magnesium salts is rare in healthy individuals with a normal diet, because excess magnesium is readily excreted in [[urine]] by the [[kidneys]]. A few cases of [[oral administration|oral]] magnesium toxicity have been described in persons with normal renal function ingesting large amounts of magnesium salts, but it is rare. If a large amount of magnesium chloride is eaten, it will have effects similar to [[magnesium sulfate]], causing diarrhea, although the sulfate also contributes to the laxative effect in magnesium sulfate, so the effect from the chloride is not as severe.\n\n=== Plant toxicity ===\n\nChloride (Cl<sup>\u2212</sup>) and magnesium (Mg<sup>2+</sup>) are both essential nutrients important for normal plant growth. Too much of either nutrient may harm a plant, although foliar chloride concentrations are more strongly related with foliar damage than magnesium. High concentrations of MgCl<sub>2</sub> ions in the soil may be toxic or change water relationships such that the plant cannot easily accumulate water and nutrients. Once inside the plant, chloride moves through the water-conducting system and accumulates at the margins of leaves or needles, where dieback occurs first. Leaves are weakened or killed, which can lead to the death of the tree.<ref name=\"colostate1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ext.colostate.edu/pubs/garden/07425.html |title=Publications \u2013 ExtensionExtension |publisher=Ext.colostate.edu |accessdate=2017-10-18 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924005210/http://www.ext.colostate.edu/pubs/garden/07425.html |archive-date=2015-09-24 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Locomotive boiler problem==\nThe presence of dissolved magnesium chloride in the well water ([[Water well#Drilled wells|bore water]]) used in locomotive boilers on the [[Trans-Australian Railway]] caused serious and expensive maintenance problems during the steam era. At no point along its route does the line cross a permanent freshwater watercourse, so bore water had to be relied on. No inexpensive treatment for the highly mineralised water was available, and locomotive boilers were lasting less than a quarter of the time normally expected.<ref>{{cite news |title=Overland Locomotive:Feed Water Problems |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article3880541 |accessdate=2014-03-11 |newspaper=The Argus |date=1927-03-21}}</ref> In the days of steam locomotion, about half the total train load was water for the engine. The line's operator, [[Commonwealth Railways]], was an early adopter of the [[Diesel locomotive#Diesel-electric|diesel-electric locomotive]].\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Acceptable daily intake]]\n* [[Magnesium oil]]\n\n== Notes and references ==\n;Notes\n{{reflist|30em}}\n;References\n* ''Handbook of Chemistry and Physics'', 71st edition, CRC Press, Ann Arbor, Michigan, 1990.\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20040314010235/http://www.usda.gov/rus/electric/engineering/2001/magnesium_chloride.htm Magnesium Chloride as a De-Icing Agent]\n* [http://www.mistralni.co.uk/msds/mmgc200.gdsbusapb.pdf MSDS file for Magnesium Chloride Hexahydrate]\n\n{{Magnesium compounds}}\n{{Chlorides}}\n{{Mineral supplements}}\n\n[[Category:Chlorides]]\n[[Category:Magnesium compounds]]\n[[Category:Metal halides]]\n[[Category:Deliquescent substances]]\n[[Category:Food additives]]\n[[Category:E-number additives]]\n", "name_user": "0m9Ep", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnesium_chloride"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Mississippi", "text_new": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Mississippi, United States}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Mississippi\n| map1            = \n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| legend1         = {{legend|#a5130f|Confirmed cases}}\n| location        = [[Mississippi]], U.S\n| first_case      = [[Forrest County, Mississippi|Forrest County]]\n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| arrival_date    = March 12, 2020<ref name=\"first\">{{Cite Web|date=12 March 2020|access-date=12 March 2020|title=First Case of Coronavirus in Mississippi|url=https://www.deltanews.tv/news/first-case-of-coronavirus-in-mississippi/article_75c2dea4-6467-11ea-ad25-13433a2a000a.html}}</ref>\n| confirmed_cases = 3,087 (as of 6pm, April 13, 2020)\n| recovery_cases  = \n| deaths          = 111\n| origin          = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], [[China]]\n| website         = [https://msdh.ms.gov/msdhsite/_static/14,0,420.html Mississippi State Department of Health]\n}}\n\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have reached the U.S. state of [[Mississippi]] in March 2020.\n\n==Timeline==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United States/Mississippi medical cases chart}}\n\nThe [[Mississippi State Department of Health]] (MSDH) confirmed their first case in the state on March 12, 2020. The individual is from [[Forrest County, Mississippi|Forrest County]], who had recently traveled to the state of Florida.<ref name=\"first\"/> Three days later, on March 15, the state had a spike in cases (4) in the state bringing the total to 10.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wcbi.com/10-coronavirus-cases-reported-mississippi/|title=10 CORONAVIRUS CASES REPORTED IN MISSISSIPPI|last=Matlock|first=Cash|date=March 15, 2020|website=WCBI-TV|language=en|access-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref> On March 16, two new cases in the state, one in [[Pearl River County, Mississippi|Pearl River County]] and another [[Monroe County, Mississippi|Monroe County]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wxxv25.com/2020/03/16/coronavirus-two-cases-covid-19-pearl-river-county-one-hancock-county/|title=CORONAVIRUS: TWO CASES OF COVID-19 IN PEARL RIVER COUNTY, ONE IN HANCOCK COUNTY|last=Keiek|first=Brantly|date=March 16, 2020|website=WXXV-TV|language=en|access-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\nOn March 17, cases in the state jumped from 12 to 21, with 4 in [[Hinds County, Mississippi|Hinds County]], 3 in [[Leflore County, Mississippi|Leflore County]], one in [[Jackson County, Mississippi|Jackson County]], and one in [[Harrison County, Mississippi|Harrison County]]. The next day, on March 18, cases spiked up to 34, with [[DeSoto County, Mississippi|DeSoto County]] seeing their first case, along with [[Madison County, Mississippi|Madison County]] and [[Perry County, Mississippi|Perry County]]. [[Bolivar County, Mississippi|Bolivar County]] saw their first 2 cases. The following day, on March 19, the state saw 16 cases and its first death.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wlbt.com/2020/03/19/health-department-confirms-mississippis-first-coronavirus-death/|title=HEALTH DEPARTMENT CONFIRMS MISSISSIPPI'S FIRST CORONAVIRUS DEATH|last=Lee|first=China|date=March 19, 2020|website=wlbt.tv|language=en|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\nHarris and Pearl River counties saw 3 new cases each, while the counties of DeSoto, Forrest, and Jackson counties saw one additional case, while at least one new case were reported in the counties of Holmes, Jones, Smith, Walthall, Wilkinson, Winston, and Yazoo. On March 20, the state saw 30 new cases, bringing the total up to 80. New cases were reported in Adams, Franklin, Humphreys, Lawrence, Lee, Marshall, Monroe, Pike, Rankin, Tippah, and Webster counties, while additional cases were reported in Coahoma, DeSoto, Hancock, Harrison, Hinds, Holmes, Jackson, and Madison counties.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wmcactionnews5.com/2020/03/13/cases-coronavirus-identified-by-miss-dept-health/|title=CASES CORONAVIRUS IDENTIFIED BY MISS DEPT HEALTH|author=WLBT.com Staff|date=March 13, 2020|website=wmcactionnews5|language=en|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\nOn March 21, the state jumped in cases, reporting 60 new cases, jumping the total to 140.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.djournal.com/news/state-news/mississippi-coronavirus-cases-up-to/article_c20d021d-ab00-5a75-81b5-a174857bb61c.html/|title=MISSISSIPPI CORONAVIRUS CASES UP TO 140|last=Burnett|first=Jayson|date=March 21, 2020|website=djournal|language=en|accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref>\nMarch 22 saw 67 new cases in the state, with most counties in the state ending up with a new case.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/news/us/coronavirus-cases-increase-to-207-in-mississippi/ar-BB11xEFv/|title=CORONAVIRUS CASES INCREASE TO 207 IN MISSISSIPPI|last=Fowler|first=Sarah|date=March 22, 2020|website=MSN News|language=en|access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Government responses==\nOn March 14, two days after the first case was announced in the state, Governor [[Tate Reeves]], declared a state of emergency, due to how big of an impact the neighboring state of Louisiana, has had with the virus. Louisiana at the time was the most infected state per capita.<ref name=\"DSE\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.clarionledger.com/story/news/2020/03/14/mississippi-coronavirus-gov-reeves-declares-state-emergency/5050744002/|title=Mississippi declares state of emergency over coronavirus as Louisiana hard hit|last=Broom|first=Brian|date=March 14, 2020|website=Clarion Ledger|language=en|access-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref> Reeves recently came back from a trip from Spain (a country hit hard by the virus) and stated that he will voluntarily work from home for precautionary purposes.<ref name=\"DSE\"/>\n\nMarch 15, [[Jackson, Mississippi|Jackson]]'s city mayor [[Chokwe Antar Lumumba]] declared civil emergency for the city.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wlbt.com/2020/03/16/jackson-mayor-declare-civil-emergency-amid-coronavirus-outbreak/|title=Jackson mayor to declare civil emergency amid coronavirus outbreak|last=Lee|first=China|date=March 15, 2020|website=WLBT|language=en|access-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 21, the mayor of [[Tupelo, Mississippi|Tupelo]], [[Jason Shelton]], imposed a [[stay-at-home order]] that went into effect early on March 22.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wtva.com/content/news/Tupelo--569001971.html/|title=Tupelo now under stay-at-home order to prevent coronavirus spread|author=Sydney Darden/Craig Ford|date=March 21, 2020|website=WVTA|language=en|access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref>\nThe same day, [[Columbus, Mississippi|Columbus]] put in a curfew from 10 pm to 6 am until further notice.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wtva.com/content/news/columbus-curfew-568998021.html/|title=Columbus implements curfew and restrictions on businesses, other gatherings|last=Carlisle|first=Zac|date=March 21, 2020|website=WVTA|language=en|access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 24, Governor Reeves issued an executive order deeming most businesses as \"essential\" including restaurants, bars and other establishments including dining in but limiting to 10 persons.  The order also banned local governments from imposing stricter orders.<ref>{{cite web |title=Gov. Tate Reeves Signs New Executive Order in Response to COVID-19 Spread |url=https://www.jacksonfreepress.com/news/2020/mar/24/gov-tate-reeves-signs-new-executive-order-slow-spr/ |website=Jackson Free Press |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> However, the wording of the executive order lead to some confusion among local governments on the authority of the state overriding that of restrictions put into place by municipalities and counties.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ganusheau |first1=Adam |title=Mayors scramble to know: Does Gov. Reeves' coronavirus declaration clash with local orders? |url=https://www.sunherald.com/news/politics-government/article241524861.html |website=Biloxi Sun Herald |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> In response to criticism and confusion expressed by the public and local officials, Governor Reeves issued a supplemental order on March 26 that clarified that stricter restrictions put into place by local governing bodies were allowed.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Cook |first1=Cathy |title=Clarifications on conflicting executive orders |url=https://www.picayuneitem.com/2020/03/local-business-restrictions-to-prevent-the-spread-of-covid-19-remain-in-place/ |website=Picayune Item |date=28 March 2020 |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn April 1, an additional executive order was issued by the Governor, announcing a state-wide shelter-in-place order, requiring all non-essential businesses to close and overrides previous allowances for dine-in services in restaurants made in the March 24 executive order.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ladd |first1=Donna |last2=Judin |first2=Nick |title=Governor Does About-Face, Issues Statewide 'Shelter In Place' For Mississippi |url=https://www.jacksonfreepress.com/news/2020/apr/01/governor-does-about-face-issues-statewide-shelter-/ |website=Jackson Free Press |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nState health officer Dr. [[Thomas Dobbs]] stated during a news conference on April 1 that MSDH is not releasing to the public the number of ventilators available and the number of healthcare workers infected with COVID-19, despite confirming that MSDH does have this information, citing the potential for fear and confusion, despite other states, like [[Louisiana]], providing these numbers.<ref>{{cite web |last1=LeMaster |first1=C.J. |title=MSDH keeps some details on Mississippi's health care readiness, capabilities from public |url=https://www.wlox.com/2020/04/04/msdh-keeps-some-details-mississippis-health-care-readiness-capabilities-public/ |website=WLOX |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Impact on sports==\nOn March 12, the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] cancelled all winter and spring tournaments, most notably the [[NCAA Division I|Division I]] [[2020 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|men]]'s and [[2020 NCAA Division I Women's Basketball Tournament|women]]'s basketball tournaments, affecting colleges and universities statewide.<ref name=ncaa>[https://www.ncaa.org/about/resources/media-center/news/ncaa-cancels-remaining-winter-and-spring-championships NCAA cancels remaining winter and spring championships] NCAA, March 12, 2020</ref> On March 16, the [[National Junior College Athletic Association]] also canceled the remainder of the winter seasons as well as the spring seasons.<ref>[https://www.mlive.com/sports/2020/03/njcaa-cancels-spring-sports-basketball-nationals-amid-coronavirus-outbreak.html NJCAA cancels spring sports, basketball nationals amid coronavirus outbreak] MLive.com, March 16, 2020</ref>\n\n==Statistics==\n.COVID-19 cases in Mississippi<ref>[https://msdh.ms.gov/msdhsite/_static/14,0,420.html#caseTable Mississippi Department of Health]</ref> as of 11:16 a.m. April 16, 2020.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|County\n|Cases\n|Deaths\n|LTCs with Outbreaks\n|-\n|[[Adams County, Mississippi|Adams]]\n|73\n|6\n|2\n|-\n|[[Alcorn County, Mississippi|Alcorn]]\n|7\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[Amite County, Mississippi|Amite]]\n|16\n|1\n|1\n|-\n|[[Attala County, Mississippi|Attala]]\n|34\n|\n|1\n|-\n|[[Benton County, Mississippi|Benton]]\n|5\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[Bolivar County, Mississippi|Bolivar]]\n|79\n|5\n|4\n|-\n|[[Calhoun County, Mississippi|Calhoun]]\n|36\n|2\n|1\n|-\n|[[Carroll County, Mississippi|Carroll]]\n|10\n|1\n|\n|-\n|[[Chickasaw County, Mississippi|Chickasaw]]\n|40\n|2\n|1\n|-\n|[[Choctaw County, Mississippi|Choctaw]]\n|11\n|1\n|\n|-\n|[[Claiborne County, Mississippi|Claiborne]]\n|8\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[Clarke County, Mississippi|Clarke]]\n|22\n|2\n|2\n|-\n|[[Clay County, Mississippi|Clay]]\n|24\n|1\n|\n|-\n|[[Coahoma County, Mississippi|Coahoma]]\n|46\n|1\n|\n|-\n|[[Copiah County, Mississippi|Copiah]]\n|41\n|1\n|\n|-\n|[[Covington County, Mississippi|Covington]]\n|28\n|\n|1\n|-\n|[[Desoto County, Mississippi|Desoto]]\n|220\n|3\n|1\n|-\n|[[Forrest County, Mississippi|Forrest]]\n|137\n|3\n|2\n|-\n|[[Franklin County, Mississippi|Franklin]]\n|15\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[George County, Mississippi|George]]\n|10\n|1\n|\n|-\n|[[Greene County, Mississippi|Greene]]\n|3\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[Grenada County, Mississippi|Grenada]]\n|19\n|\n|1\n|-\n|[[Hancock County, Mississippi|Hancock]]\n|50\n|5\n|2\n|-\n|[[Harrison County, Mississippi|Harrison]]\n|144\n|5\n|3\n|-\n|[[Hinds County, Mississippi|Hinds]]\n|325\n|5\n|5\n|-\n|[[Holmes County, Mississippi|Holmes]]\n|58\n|4\n|\n|-\n|[[Humphreys County, Mississippi|Humphreys]]\n|12\n|3\n|1\n|-\n|[[Issaquena County, Mississippi|Issaquena]]\n|0\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[Itawamba County, Mississippi|Itawamba]]\n|21\n|1\n|1\n|-\n|[[Jackson County, Mississippi|Jackson]]\n|201\n|6\n|2\n|-\n|[[Jasper County, Mississippi|Jasper]]\n|22\n|1\n|\n|-\n|[[Jefferson County, Mississippi|Jefferson]]\n|4\n|\n|1\n|-\n|[[Jefferson Davis County, Mississippi|Jefferson Davis]]\n|8\n|1\n|\n|-\n|[[Jones County, Mississippi|Jones]]\n|63\n|\n|2\n|-\n|[[Kemper County, Mississippi|Kemper]]\n|17\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[Lafayette County, Mississippi|Lafayette]]\n|40\n|3\n|1\n|-\n|[[Lamar County, Mississippi|Lamar]]\n|59\n|1\n|\n|-\n|[[Lauderdale County, Mississippi|Lauderdale]]\n|190\n|14\n|7\n|-\n|[[Lawrence County, Mississippi|Lawrence]]\n|14\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[Leake County, Mississippi|Leake]]\n|64\n|1\n|\n|-\n|[[Lee County, Mississippi|Lee]]\n|54\n|4\n|\n|-\n|[[Leflore County, Mississippi|Leflore]]\n|75\n|6\n|2\n|-\n|[[Lincoln County, Mississippi|Lincoln]]\n|102\n|6\n|2\n|-\n|[[Lowndes County, Mississippi|Lowndes]]\n|32\n|1\n|2\n|-\n|[[Madison County, Mississippi|Madison]]\n|127\n|3\n|2\n|-\n|[[Marion County, Mississippi|Marion]]\n|39\n|\n|1\n|-\n|[[Marshall County, Mississippi|Marshall]]\n|39\n|2\n|\n|-\n|[[Monroe County, Mississippi|Monroe]]\n|62\n|4\n|2\n|-\n|[[Montgomery County, Mississippi|Montgomery]]\n|15\n|1\n|\n|-\n|[[Neshoba County, Mississippi|Neshoba]]\n|55\n|1\n|\n|-\n|[[Newton County, Mississippi|Newton]]\n|21\n|\n|1\n|-\n|[[Noxubee County, Mississippi|Noxubee]]\n|20\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[Oktibbeha County, Mississippi|Oktibbeha]]\n|43\n|2\n|2\n|-\n|[[Panola County, Mississippi|Panola]]\n|30\n|2\n|\n|-\n|[[Pearl River County, Mississippi|Pearl River]]\n|119\n|10\n|2\n|-\n|[[Perry County, Mississippi|Perry]]\n|22\n|1\n|\n|-\n|[[Pike County, Mississippi|Pike]]\n|97\n|2\n|2\n|-\n|[[Pontotoc County, Mississippi|Pontotoc]]\n|17\n|2\n|\n|-\n|[[Prentiss County, Mississippi|Prentiss]]\n|16\n|\n|2\n|-\n|[[Quitman County, Mississippi|Quitman]]\n|13\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[Rankin County, Mississippi|Rankin]]\n|130\n|2\n|1\n|-\n|[[Scott County, Mississippi|Scott]]\n|106\n|\n|1\n|-\n|[[Sharkey County, Mississippi|Sharkey]]\n|3\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[Simpson County, Mississippi|Simpson]]\n|14\n|\n|1\n|-\n|[[Smith County, Mississippi|Smith]]\n|39\n|1\n|1\n|-\n|[[Stone County, Mississippi|Stone]]\n|17\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[Sunflower County, Mississippi|Sunflower]]\n|46\n|2\n|\n|-\n|[[Tallahatchie County, Mississippi|Tallahatchie]]\n|8\n|1\n|\n|-\n|[[Tate County, Mississippi|Tate]]\n|29\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[Tippah County, Mississippi|Tippah]]\n|46\n|7\n|1\n|-\n|[[Tishomingo County, Mississippi|Tishomingo]]\n|3\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[Tunica County, Mississippi|Tunica]]\n|30\n|1\n|1\n|-\n|[[Union County, Mississippi|Union]]\n|9\n|1\n|1\n|-\n|[[Walthall County, Mississippi|Walthall]]\n|23\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[Warren County, Mississippi|Warren]]\n|18\n|1\n|\n|-\n|[[Washington County, Mississippi|Washington]]\n|70\n|3\n|1\n|-\n|[[Wayne County, Mississippi|Wayne]]\n|10\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[Webster County, Mississippi|Webster]]\n|15\n|1\n|\n|-\n|[[Wilkinson County, Mississippi|Wilkinson]]\n|55\n|4\n|1\n|-\n|[[Winston County, Mississippi|Winston]]\n|29\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[Yalobusha County, Mississippi|Yalobusha]]\n|15\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[Yazoo County, Mississippi|Yazoo]]\n|85\n|1\n|\n|-\n|'''Total (statewide)'''\n|'''3,974'''\n|'''152'''\n|'''69'''\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://msdh.ms.gov/msdhsite/_static/14,0,420.html Coronavirus information] from the [[Mississippi State Department of Health]]\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n{{Portal bar|Mississippi|Medicine|Viruses|Coronavirus disease 2019|Pandemic}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States by state|Mississippi]]\n[[Category:2020 in Mississippi|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Disasters in Mississippi]]\n[[Category:Health in Mississippi]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Mississippi, United States}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Mississippi\n| map1            = \n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| legend1         = {{legend|#a5130f|Confirmed cases}}\n| location        = [[Mississippi]], U.S\n| first_case      = [[Forrest County, Mississippi|Forrest County]]\n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| arrival_date    = March 12, 2020<ref name=\"first\">{{Cite Web|date=12 March 2020|access-date=12 March 2020|title=First Case of Coronavirus in Mississippi|url=https://www.deltanews.tv/news/first-case-of-coronavirus-in-mississippi/article_75c2dea4-6467-11ea-ad25-13433a2a000a.html}}</ref>\n| confirmed_cases = 3,087 (as of 6pm, April 13, 2020)\n| recovery_cases  = \n| deaths          = 111\n| origin          = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], [[China]]\n| website         = [https://msdh.ms.gov/msdhsite/_static/14,0,420.html Mississippi State Department of Health]\n}}\n\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have reached the U.S. state of [[Mississippi]] in March 2020.\n\n==Timeline==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United States/Mississippi medical cases chart}}\n\nThe [[Mississippi State Department of Health]] (MSDH) confirmed their first case in the state on March 12, 2020. The individual is from [[Forrest County, Mississippi|Forrest County]], who had recently traveled to the state of Florida.<ref name=\"first\"/> Three days later, on March 15, the state had a spike in cases (4) in the state bringing the total to 10.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wcbi.com/10-coronavirus-cases-reported-mississippi/|title=10 CORONAVIRUS CASES REPORTED IN MISSISSIPPI|last=Matlock|first=Cash|date=March 15, 2020|website=WCBI-TV|language=en|access-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref> On March 16, two new cases in the state, one in [[Pearl River County, Mississippi|Pearl River County]] and another [[Monroe County, Mississippi|Monroe County]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wxxv25.com/2020/03/16/coronavirus-two-cases-covid-19-pearl-river-county-one-hancock-county/|title=CORONAVIRUS: TWO CASES OF COVID-19 IN PEARL RIVER COUNTY, ONE IN HANCOCK COUNTY|last=Keiek|first=Brantly|date=March 16, 2020|website=WXXV-TV|language=en|access-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\nOn March 17, cases in the state jumped from 12 to 21, with 4 in [[Hinds County, Mississippi|Hinds County]], 3 in [[Leflore County, Mississippi|Leflore County]], one in [[Jackson County, Mississippi|Jackson County]], and one in [[Harrison County, Mississippi|Harrison County]]. The next day, on March 18, cases spiked up to 34, with [[DeSoto County, Mississippi|DeSoto County]] seeing their first case, along with [[Madison County, Mississippi|Madison County]] and [[Perry County, Mississippi|Perry County]]. [[Bolivar County, Mississippi|Bolivar County]] saw their first 2 cases. The following day, on March 19, the state saw 16 cases and its first death.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wlbt.com/2020/03/19/health-department-confirms-mississippis-first-coronavirus-death/|title=HEALTH DEPARTMENT CONFIRMS MISSISSIPPI'S FIRST CORONAVIRUS DEATH|last=Lee|first=China|date=March 19, 2020|website=wlbt.tv|language=en|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\nHarris and Pearl River counties saw 3 new cases each, while the counties of DeSoto, Forrest, and Jackson counties saw one additional case, while at least one new case were reported in the counties of Holmes, Jones, Smith, Walthall, Wilkinson, Winston, and Yazoo. On March 20, the state saw 30 new cases, bringing the total up to 80. New cases were reported in Adams, Franklin, Humphreys, Lawrence, Lee, Marshall, Monroe, Pike, Rankin, Tippah, and Webster counties, while additional cases were reported in Coahoma, DeSoto, Hancock, Harrison, Hinds, Holmes, Jackson, and Madison counties.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wmcactionnews5.com/2020/03/13/cases-coronavirus-identified-by-miss-dept-health/|title=CASES CORONAVIRUS IDENTIFIED BY MISS DEPT HEALTH|author=WLBT.com Staff|date=March 13, 2020|website=wmcactionnews5|language=en|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\nOn March 21, the state jumped in cases, reporting 60 new cases, jumping the total to 140.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.djournal.com/news/state-news/mississippi-coronavirus-cases-up-to/article_c20d021d-ab00-5a75-81b5-a174857bb61c.html/|title=MISSISSIPPI CORONAVIRUS CASES UP TO 140|last=Burnett|first=Jayson|date=March 21, 2020|website=djournal|language=en|accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref>\nMarch 22 saw 67 new cases in the state, with most counties in the state ending up with a new case.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/news/us/coronavirus-cases-increase-to-207-in-mississippi/ar-BB11xEFv/|title=CORONAVIRUS CASES INCREASE TO 207 IN MISSISSIPPI|last=Fowler|first=Sarah|date=March 22, 2020|website=MSN News|language=en|access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Government responses==\nOn March 14, two days after the first case was announced in the state, Governor [[Tate Reeves]], declared a state of emergency, due to how big of an impact the neighboring state of Louisiana, has had with the virus. Louisiana at the time was the most infected state per capita.<ref name=\"DSE\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.clarionledger.com/story/news/2020/03/14/mississippi-coronavirus-gov-reeves-declares-state-emergency/5050744002/|title=Mississippi declares state of emergency over coronavirus as Louisiana hard hit|last=Broom|first=Brian|date=March 14, 2020|website=Clarion Ledger|language=en|access-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref> Reeves recently came back from a trip from Spain (a country hit hard by the virus) and stated that he will voluntarily work from home for precautionary purposes.<ref name=\"DSE\"/>\n\nMarch 15, [[Jackson, Mississippi|Jackson]]'s city mayor [[Chokwe Antar Lumumba]] declared civil emergency for the city.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wlbt.com/2020/03/16/jackson-mayor-declare-civil-emergency-amid-coronavirus-outbreak/|title=Jackson mayor to declare civil emergency amid coronavirus outbreak|last=Lee|first=China|date=March 15, 2020|website=WLBT|language=en|access-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 21, the mayor of [[Tupelo, Mississippi|Tupelo]], [[Jason Shelton]], imposed a [[stay-at-home order]] that went into effect early on March 22.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wtva.com/content/news/Tupelo--569001971.html/|title=Tupelo now under stay-at-home order to prevent coronavirus spread|author=Sydney Darden/Craig Ford|date=March 21, 2020|website=WVTA|language=en|access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref>\nThe same day, [[Columbus, Mississippi|Columbus]] put in a curfew from 10 pm to 6 am until further notice.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wtva.com/content/news/columbus-curfew-568998021.html/|title=Columbus implements curfew and restrictions on businesses, other gatherings|last=Carlisle|first=Zac|date=March 21, 2020|website=WVTA|language=en|access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 24, Governor Reeves issued an executive order deeming most businesses as \"essential\" including restaurants, bars and other establishments including dining in but limiting to 10 persons.  The order also banned local governments from imposing stricter orders.<ref>{{cite web |title=Gov. Tate Reeves Signs New Executive Order in Response to COVID-19 Spread |url=https://www.jacksonfreepress.com/news/2020/mar/24/gov-tate-reeves-signs-new-executive-order-slow-spr/ |website=Jackson Free Press |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> However, the wording of the executive order lead to some confusion among local governments on the authority of the state overriding that of restrictions put into place by municipalities and counties.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ganusheau |first1=Adam |title=Mayors scramble to know: Does Gov. Reeves' coronavirus declaration clash with local orders? |url=https://www.sunherald.com/news/politics-government/article241524861.html |website=Biloxi Sun Herald |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> In response to criticism and confusion expressed by the public and local officials, Governor Reeves issued a supplemental order on March 26 that clarified that stricter restrictions put into place by local governing bodies were allowed.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Cook |first1=Cathy |title=Clarifications on conflicting executive orders |url=https://www.picayuneitem.com/2020/03/local-business-restrictions-to-prevent-the-spread-of-covid-19-remain-in-place/ |website=Picayune Item |date=28 March 2020 |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn April 1, an additional executive order was issued by the Governor, announcing a state-wide shelter-in-place order, requiring all non-essential businesses to close and overrides previous allowances for dine-in services in restaurants made in the March 24 executive order.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ladd |first1=Donna |last2=Judin |first2=Nick |title=Governor Does About-Face, Issues Statewide 'Shelter In Place' For Mississippi |url=https://www.jacksonfreepress.com/news/2020/apr/01/governor-does-about-face-issues-statewide-shelter-/ |website=Jackson Free Press |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nState health officer Dr. [[Thomas Dobbs]] stated during a news conference on April 1 that MSDH is not releasing to the public the number of ventilators available and the number of healthcare workers infected with COVID-19, despite confirming that MSDH does have this information, citing the potential for fear and confusion, despite other states, like [[Louisiana]], providing these numbers.<ref>{{cite web |last1=LeMaster |first1=C.J. |title=MSDH keeps some details on Mississippi's health care readiness, capabilities from public |url=https://www.wlox.com/2020/04/04/msdh-keeps-some-details-mississippis-health-care-readiness-capabilities-public/ |website=WLOX |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Impact on sports==\nOn March 12, the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] cancelled all winter and spring tournaments, most notably the [[NCAA Division I|Division I]] [[2020 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|men]]'s and [[2020 NCAA Division I Women's Basketball Tournament|women]]'s basketball tournaments, affecting colleges and universities statewide.<ref name=ncaa>[https://www.ncaa.org/about/resources/media-center/news/ncaa-cancels-remaining-winter-and-spring-championships NCAA cancels remaining winter and spring championships] NCAA, March 12, 2020</ref> On March 16, the [[National Junior College Athletic Association]] also canceled the remainder of the winter seasons as well as the spring seasons.<ref>[https://www.mlive.com/sports/2020/03/njcaa-cancels-spring-sports-basketball-nationals-amid-coronavirus-outbreak.html NJCAA cancels spring sports, basketball nationals amid coronavirus outbreak] MLive.com, March 16, 2020</ref>\n\n==Statistics==\n.COVID-19 cases in Mississippi<ref>[https://msdh.ms.gov/msdhsite/_static/14,0,420.html#caseTable Mississippi Department of Health]</ref> as of 6 p.m. April 12, 2020.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|County\n|Cases\n|Deaths\n|LTCs with Outbreaks\n|-\n|[[Adams County, Mississippi|Adams]]\n|73\n|6\n|2\n|-\n|[[Alcorn County, Mississippi|Alcorn]]\n|7\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[Amite County, Mississippi|Amite]]\n|16\n|1\n|1\n|-\n|[[Attala County, Mississippi|Attala]]\n|34\n|\n|1\n|-\n|[[Benton County, Mississippi|Benton]]\n|5\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[Bolivar County, Mississippi|Bolivar]]\n|79\n|5\n|4\n|-\n|[[Calhoun County, Mississippi|Calhoun]]\n|36\n|2\n|1\n|-\n|[[Carroll County, Mississippi|Carroll]]\n|10\n|1\n|\n|-\n|[[Chickasaw County, Mississippi|Chickasaw]]\n|40\n|2\n|1\n|-\n|[[Choctaw County, Mississippi|Choctaw]]\n|11\n|1\n|\n|-\n|[[Claiborne County, Mississippi|Claiborne]]\n|8\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[Clarke County, Mississippi|Clarke]]\n|22\n|2\n|2\n|-\n|[[Clay County, Mississippi|Clay]]\n|24\n|1\n|\n|-\n|[[Coahoma County, Mississippi|Coahoma]]\n|46\n|1\n|\n|-\n|[[Copiah County, Mississippi|Copiah]]\n|41\n|1\n|\n|-\n|[[Covington County, Mississippi|Covington]]\n|28\n|\n|1\n|-\n|[[Desoto County, Mississippi|Desoto]]\n|220\n|3\n|1\n|-\n|[[Forrest County, Mississippi|Forrest]]\n|137\n|3\n|2\n|-\n|[[Franklin County, Mississippi|Franklin]]\n|15\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[George County, Mississippi|George]]\n|10\n|1\n|\n|-\n|[[Greene County, Mississippi|Greene]]\n|3\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[Grenada County, Mississippi|Grenada]]\n|19\n|\n|1\n|-\n|[[Hancock County, Mississippi|Hancock]]\n|50\n|5\n|2\n|-\n|[[Harrison County, Mississippi|Harrison]]\n|144\n|5\n|3\n|-\n|[[Hinds County, Mississippi|Hinds]]\n|325\n|5\n|5\n|-\n|[[Holmes County, Mississippi|Holmes]]\n|58\n|4\n|\n|-\n|[[Humphreys County, Mississippi|Humphreys]]\n|12\n|3\n|1\n|-\n|[[Issaquena County, Mississippi|Issaquena]]\n|0\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[Itawamba County, Mississippi|Itawamba]]\n|21\n|1\n|1\n|-\n|[[Jackson County, Mississippi|Jackson]]\n|201\n|6\n|2\n|-\n|[[Jasper County, Mississippi|Jasper]]\n|22\n|1\n|\n|-\n|[[Jefferson County, Mississippi|Jefferson]]\n|4\n|\n|1\n|-\n|[[Jefferson Davis County, Mississippi|Jefferson Davis]]\n|8\n|1\n|\n|-\n|[[Jones County, Mississippi|Jones]]\n|63\n|\n|2\n|-\n|[[Kemper County, Mississippi|Kemper]]\n|17\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[Lafayette County, Mississippi|Lafayette]]\n|40\n|3\n|1\n|-\n|[[Lamar County, Mississippi|Lamar]]\n|59\n|1\n|\n|-\n|[[Lauderdale County, Mississippi|Lauderdale]]\n|190\n|14\n|7\n|-\n|[[Lawrence County, Mississippi|Lawrence]]\n|14\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[Leake County, Mississippi|Leake]]\n|64\n|1\n|\n|-\n|[[Lee 